define({"topics" : [{"title":"PDF customization approaches","shortdesc":"<p class=\"shortdesc\">Various methods may be used to customize the PDF output produced by the DITA Open Toolkit. Each of these     approaches have advantages and shortcomings that should be considered when preparing a customization project. Some     of these methods are considered “anti-patterns” with disadvantages that outweigh their apparent appeal. In most     cases, you should create a custom PDF plug-in.</p>","href":"topics\/pdf-customization-approaches.html","attributes": {"data-id":"pdf_customization_approaches",},"menu": {"hasChildren":false,},"tocID":"pdf_customization_approaches-d50e1294","topics":[]},{"title":"Types of custom PDF plug-ins","shortdesc":"<p class=\"shortdesc\">There are two common types of plug-ins: A plug-in that simply sets the DITA-OT parameters to be used when a     PDF is generated, and a plug-in that overrides aspects of the base DITA-OT PDF transformation. A plug-in can, of     course, do both of these things.</p>","href":"topics\/pdf-customization-plugin-types.html","attributes": {"data-id":"types-pdf-customization-plugins",},"menu": {"hasChildren":false,},"tocID":"types-pdf-customization-plugins-d50e1315","topics":[]},{"title":"PDF plug-in structure","shortdesc":"<p class=\"shortdesc\">In cases that require substantial customizations, it is often useful to organize the files in a folder     structure that mimics the hierarchy of the default PDF plug-in. This method facilitates comparisons with the default     settings in the base PDF plug-in and makes it easier to migrate customizations to new toolkit versions.</p>","href":"topics\/pdf-plugin-structure.html","attributes": {"data-id":"pdf-plugin-structure",},"menu": {"hasChildren":false,},"tocID":"pdf-plugin-structure-d50e1336","topics":[]},{"title":"Simple PDF plug-in example","shortdesc":"<p class=\"shortdesc\">This scenario walks through the process of creating a very simple plug-in       (<code class=\"ph codeph\">com.example.print-pdf</code>) that creates a new transformation type: <span class=\"keyword option\">print-pdf</span>. </p>","href":"topics\/pdf-customization-example.html","attributes": {"data-id":"dita2pdf-customization",},"menu": {"hasChildren":false,},"tocID":"dita2pdf-customization-d50e1357","topics":[]},{"title":"Custom PDF plug-in resources","shortdesc":"<p class=\"shortdesc\">There are several external resources that can help you generate and refine custom PDF plug-ins for the DITA     Open Toolkit.</p>","href":"topics\/pdf-customization-resources.html","attributes": {"data-id":"ID",},"menu": {"hasChildren":false,},"tocID":"ID-d50e1384","topics":[]},{"title":"Generating revision bars","shortdesc":"<p class=\"shortdesc\">If you use Antenna House Formatter or RenderX XEP, you can generate revision bars in your PDF output by     using the <code class=\"keyword markupname xmlatt\">@changebar</code> attribute of the DITAVAL <code class=\"keyword markupname xmlelement\">&lt;revprop&gt;</code> element. </p>","href":"topics\/pdf2-creating-change-bars.html","attributes": {"data-id":"concept_gsc_vcf_vs",},"menu": {"hasChildren":false,},"tocID":"concept_gsc_vcf_vs-d50e1405","topics":[]}]});